# Mono-rotate overlay (BL-448): one resident agent plays every pipeline role

Read this when your swarm was launched with the `mono-rotate` pack config.

## Pipeline shape

- Full chain, same as `swarmforge/PIPELINE.md`: **coder → cleaner → architect
  → hardender → documenter → QA**. No specifier in the rotation (it already
  lives on `master` alongside the coordinator in every pack; the coordinator
  routes directly to coder as intake allows).
- Every gate the full pack runs still runs, unabridged: acceptance, coverage,
  mutation/no-surviving-mutants, CRAP<=6, QA's final pass. The memory saving
  is ONLY that one process serves every role in turn, never that a gate is
  skipped or made lighter. Slower wall-clock is the accepted cost.
- **You are that one resident process.** Only your window's role (the first
  `window` line in `mono-rotate.conf`) ever gets a real tmux session under
  this pack — every other pipeline role in the conf still has its own
  worktree and its own `roles.tsv` entry (so its mailbox resolves correctly
  the moment you become it), but no process of its own until you do.

## How you rotate

Each pipeline role's own `swarmforge/roles/<role>.prompt` — read it, unchanged
— is still the authority for THAT role's substance (what it owns, how it
hands off, its idle behavior). This overlay only adds: **when a role you are
currently playing finishes its handoff, you do not go idle as that role — you
become the next one.**

Concretely, once you've sent your `git_handoff` (or, for the terminal QA
stage, once your parcel-ending action is done) and would otherwise wait for
`ready_for_next.sh`:

1. Note which role you just handed the parcel to (the `to:` field of the
   handoff you just sent — you already know it, you wrote it).
2. Look up that role's own worktree path in `.swarmforge/roles.tsv` (one row
   per role: `role<TAB>worktree-name<TAB>worktree-path<TAB>...`).
3. `export SWARMFORGE_ROLE='<next-role>'`, `cd '<next-role-worktree-path>'`,
   and prepend that worktree's own `swarmforge/scripts` to `PATH` — this is
   the same per-role wiring your OWN launch script already did for you, done
   by hand for your new identity (mailbox resolution is `SWARMFORGE_ROLE` +
   `roles.tsv` driven, never tied to which physical pane asks — the same
   handoff mailbox layout every dedicated-process pack already uses).
4. Re-read `swarmforge/constitution.prompt` (recursively) and
   `swarmforge/roles/<next-role>.prompt`, exactly as if you had just been
   started fresh as that role — because, for the purposes of doing that
   role's work honestly, you have.
5. Run `ready_for_next.sh`. It will find the very handoff you just sent,
   sitting in that role's own inbox.

## The independence caveat — read this before treating a bounce as passed

SwarmForge's quality model rests on role INDEPENDENCE: a downstream role
bounces the upstream role's work with fresh eyes. Under mono-rotate, you are
both sides of every one of those reviews. That is a real, load-bearing
reduction in independence, not a formality — do not paper over it:

- When you become cleaner reviewing your own just-finished coder work (and
  so on down the chain), evaluate it as if a stranger had handed it to you,
  not as "I already know this is fine." Re-derive from the ticket and the
  code, not from what you remember deciding a minute ago.
- Do not wave a gate through because you personally just wrote the thing it
  is checking. If you would bounce this work coming from someone else,
  bounce it now.
- **Automating a genuine context reset between roles (so a later stage is
  not merely re-reading its own immediately-prior reasoning) is a deferred,
  architect-owned mechanism decision** — this pass ships the pack
  composition (one process, every role's worktree provisioned, gates
  unabridged) and this manual rotation discipline, not an automatic
  `/clear`-and-rebootstrap watcher. Until one exists, step 4 above — a
  genuinely fresh, skeptical read of the new role's own prompt and the
  ticket, not a carried-over assumption — is what stands in for it.

## Coordinator on this pack

- Unchanged: orchestrate only (backlog intake, handoffs, stall chasing,
  post-QA bookkeeping). It is reserved infrastructure, never part of the
  rotation, and always gets its own separate session.

## Sending handoffs

- Same as every other pack: `swarm_handoff.sh <draft-file>`, never write
  directly into `inbox/new/`. See `swarmforge/handoff-protocol.md` for the
  draft format.
